00:29:22.240 --> 00:29:26.200
cancer screening tests? And when I was first developing this, I was

494
00:29:26.260 --> 00:29:29.850
moving, because this was a career award, from the area of cancer survivorship into

495
00:29:29.920 --> 00:29:32.530
cancer prevention. So colorectal cancer screening was a new

496
00:29:34.340 --> 00:29:38.220
thing for me. And when I was developing this, I met with a

497
00:29:38.260 --> 00:29:42.040
gastroenterologist and he said, "You know, diabetes patients should

498
00:29:42.140 --> 00:29:45.480
all receive colonoscopies, especially if

499
00:29:46.740 --> 00:29:50.500
FQHCs are inconsistently implementing evidence-based

500
00:29:50.520 --> 00:29:54.410
practices." And the power of community-based participatory

501
00:29:54.480 --> 00:29:58.380
research is that if you talk to people who work in FQHCs, they'll tell you that

502
00:29:58.440 --> 00:30:01.520
that is an infeasible strategy, out of the gate.

503
00:30:02.060 --> 00:30:05.520
So while it might sound like the best evidence, it's not a thing that's going to

504
00:30:05.580 --> 00:30:06.820
work in these contexts.

505
00:30:08.440 --> 00:30:12.120
SoFirst, in the framing of the research question was

506
00:30:12.160 --> 00:30:14.520
developing a case for prioritizing patients with

507
00:30:15.760 --> 00:30:18.860
diabetes for colorectal cancer screening in FQHCs.

508
00:30:19.350 --> 00:30:23.250
Why would we want to do that? There is no guideline that says that we should

509
00:30:23.260 --> 00:30:27.010
prioritize patients with diabetes for colorectal cancer screening.

510
00:30:27.020 --> 00:30:31.000
But what we do know about this context is there is a long implementation lag.

511
00:30:31.420 --> 00:30:34.660
So the first landmark study that the evidence base

512
00:30:35.680 --> 00:30:38.140
was founded upon was in 1996.

513
00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:42.560
In 12 years, 50% of the US population was receiving

514
00:30:44.780 --> 00:30:46.680
colorectal cancer screening nationally.

515
00:30:48.360 --> 00:30:51.260
In 2020, we reached 72%

516
00:30:51.300 --> 00:30:55.100
nationally. Twenty-eight years later, we still have

517
00:30:55.140 --> 00:30:58.740
not met the 50% threshold for colorectal cancer screening in the

518
00:30:58.900 --> 00:31:02.869
FQHC space. That's despite this being the most widely

519
00:31:02.960 --> 00:31:06.180
studied screening process in the NHI

520
00:31:06.280 --> 00:31:09.480
portfolio. So it's not for lack of trying,

521
00:31:10.600 --> 00:31:13.920
not at the research level and not at the practice level either.

522
00:31:14.980 --> 00:31:17.280
So why would we focus on patients with diabetes?

523
00:31:17.480 --> 00:31:21.400
Well, patients with diabetes are 27% more likely to have a

524
00:31:21.420 --> 00:31:23.700
colorectal cancer diagnosis in their lifetime.

525
00:31:24.260 --> 00:31:28.190
And upon diagnosis, patients with diabetes experience more complications and

526
00:31:28.220 --> 00:31:30.320
morbidity and greater mortality.

527
00:31:31.120 --> 00:31:35.000
And we know that colorectal cancer screening, when implemented in an

528
00:31:35.060 --> 00:31:38.320
evidence-based manner, can prevent colorectal

529
00:31:38.380 --> 00:31:41.980
cancer from happening, or it can be detected early

530
00:31:42.040 --> 00:31:44.800
where it's much more easily treatable.

531
00:31:45.940 --> 00:31:49.800
So who in the population is benefiting from this

532
00:31:49.860 --> 00:31:53.350
evidence? I would argue that we don't have an evidence problem in

533
00:31:53.360 --> 00:31:54.320
colorectal cancer

534
00:31:56.700 --> 00:32:00.640
early detection. We have an implementation problem, and that's largely

535
00:32:00.700 --> 00:32:01.100
based

536
00:32:02.200 --> 00:32:03.900
on resources. So

537
00:32:04.820 --> 00:32:08.720
we know that socioeconomic factors, those drivers, are what

538
00:32:08.760 --> 00:32:10.620
is causing these disparities.

539
00:32:11.700 --> 00:32:15.420
And when we think about the context of FQHCs,

540
00:32:15.860 --> 00:32:19.570
we also need to think about the patient population and in this

541
00:32:19.600 --> 00:32:21.960
context, because patients with diabetes in

542
00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:25.540
FQHCs do not have the same

543
00:32:25.580 --> 00:32:29.000
equivalent burden of diabetes as a general population.

544
00:32:29.640 --> 00:32:32.960
Thirty to 32% of FQHC patients have poor

545
00:32:34.300 --> 00:32:35.140
glucose control.

546
00:32:37.040 --> 00:32:40.960
And patients with diabetes are about two times more likely

547
00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:43.180
to have poor control than the general population.

548
00:32:43.680 --> 00:32:46.620
So in a busy primary care clinic, what that means

549
00:32:47.620 --> 00:32:51.360
is that a provider needs to decide whether or not to prioritize a patient's glucose

550
00:32:51.400 --> 00:32:53.840
control or their general preventive screening.

551
00:32:57.060 --> 00:33:00.980
So I'm going to focus today on the last two aims of my study to take

552
00:33:01.020 --> 00:33:04.860
us through the story of how we got to the implementation strategies through this

553
00:33:04.880 --> 00:33:07.319
participatory engaged process.

554
00:33:08.340 --> 00:33:12.130
And then once we developed those strategies and identified them,

555
00:33:12.460 --> 00:33:15.730
we developed a toolkit, and then we delivered a tailored,

556
00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:16.930
facilitated

557
00:33:17.960 --> 00:33:20.460
practice change approach in three practices.

558
00:33:20.700 --> 00:33:23.090
I'm going to just tell you the story of two for today,

559
00:33:24.160 --> 00:33:28.070
and you'll have to wait for the paper for the outcomes

560
00:33:28.200 --> 00:33:31.380
because they'll be coming to me hopefully next month.

561
00:33:33.140 --> 00:33:35.400
But there's lots to talk about in getting there.

562
00:33:36.300 --> 00:33:40.080
So during the K99, I did an implementation science

563
00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:43.340
scholars program that was out of Wash U.

564
00:33:43.620 --> 00:33:47.500
And at the time, I think right before then, Ross Bronson, who

565
00:33:47.540 --> 00:33:51.460
was one of the MPIs who led that, had published this "Implementation Science in

566
00:33:51.500 --> 00:33:55.080
Health Equity." How can we do better in implementation science?

567
00:33:55.300 --> 00:33:56.350
And what

568
00:33:57.340 --> 00:33:59.540
my research focused on mainly was

569
00:34:00.420 --> 00:34:03.240
designing and tailoring the implementation strategies.

570
00:34:03.340 --> 00:34:07.080
But the highlighted pieces here are the things that I would say that

571
00:34:07.600 --> 00:34:11.281
my study attended to prior to this being brought to the

572
00:34:11.321 --> 00:34:14.920
fore. This was being done, I think, before this, but I think it

573
00:34:14.980 --> 00:34:16.640
highlights how can we do better.

574
00:34:19.140 --> 00:34:20.460
So implementation mapping.

575
00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:24.060
There are five steps in the implementation

576
00:34:25.380 --> 00:34:27.040
mapping process that I'm going to take us through.

577
00:34:27.120 --> 00:34:30.939
So the first is the needs assessment and identification of potential

578
00:34:30.980 --> 00:34:34.970
adopters. So who needs this? What do we need them

579
00:34:34.980 --> 00:34:37.031
to do? And why does it matter?

580
00:34:38.180 --> 00:34:38.980
So the what.

581
00:34:40.100 --> 00:34:43.020
What are the colorectal cancer screenings by test type in these

582
00:34:43.060 --> 00:34:46.960
settings? Which populations are being missed?

583
00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:48.761
What are the consequences for that group?

584
00:34:50.140 --> 00:34:53.580
The why. Why is it being missed? And this is at every

585
00:34:53.620 --> 00:34:56.781
level, and then the interactions between those levels.

586
00:34:57.840 --> 00:35:00.200
So who are the potential adopters?

587
00:35:00.780 --> 00:35:02.240
And who do we need to do what?

588
00:35:04.260 --> 00:35:06.840
Then the second piece of this, which was the focus of...

589
00:35:07.010 --> 00:35:10.800
So aim one of this K99 focused on this

590
00:35:10.860 --> 00:35:13.240
first step. Then we looked at

591
00:35:14.040 --> 00:35:16.860
statement of the adoption and change objectives.

592
00:35:16.900 --> 00:35:20.340
So the tasks required to adopt, implement, and maintain a program.

593
00:35:22.480 --> 00:35:26.460
Next, we choose theoretical models and select implementation strategies, the how.

594
00:35:26.980 --> 00:35:30.640
This study was guided by the EPIS framework, which is a

595
00:35:30.680 --> 00:35:34.540
process framework that really looks at the

596
00:35:34.600 --> 00:35:38.360
pieces of the how and the why of doing the different

597
00:35:38.370 --> 00:35:41.690
strategies. So it's the

598
00:35:44.160 --> 00:35:47.820
dynamic of change process model. But we also focus

599
00:35:47.860 --> 00:35:51.520
heavily on the thing which is not emphasized in this model.

600
00:35:51.920 --> 00:35:55.790
To Dr. Islam's point, we borrow from other models when it fits

601
00:35:55.880 --> 00:35:56.399
the question.

602
00:35:57.360 --> 00:36:00.180
And then using taxonomies of theories to address individual and

603
00:36:00.300 --> 00:36:02.380
organizational level strategies.

604
00:36:03.180 --> 00:36:06.700
The fourth step is producing implementation protocols and materials and

605
00:36:06.740 --> 00:36:08.410
evaluate implementation outcomes.

606
00:36:08.900 --> 00:36:12.560
And you can do this implementation mapping process a number of

607
00:36:12.620 --> 00:36:16.400
ways. The way that we did it for this study was using an implementation planning

608
00:36:16.460 --> 00:36:20.340
group, which included diverse implementation actors from a

609
00:36:20.420 --> 00:36:22.500
variety of FQHCs in New Jersey.

610
00:36:23.860 --> 00:36:27.520
We recruited 18 differentClinicians,

611
00:36:27.980 --> 00:36:30.100
members of the Department of Health who ran

612
00:36:31.440 --> 00:36:32.820
cancer screening and

613
00:36:34.440 --> 00:36:38.420
minority health initiatives. We included the NJ SEED

614
00:36:38.520 --> 00:36:41.460
program, which is our safety net screening program

615
00:36:42.500 --> 00:36:45.740
liaison and we had about 10 members from

616
00:36:45.920 --> 00:36:49.360
FQHCs that included social workers, executive

617
00:36:49.420 --> 00:36:50.220
directors,

618
00:36:51.040 --> 00:36:54.699
patient navigators, physicians, advanced practice nurses.

619
00:36:55.980 --> 00:36:59.600
So at the first meeting, what we did was develop a charter.

620
00:37:00.100 --> 00:37:04.060
So what we wanted this team to do was determine the

621
00:37:04.120 --> 00:37:07.740
targets for optimization of colorectal cancer screening for patients with

622
00:37:07.780 --> 00:37:08.500
diabetes.

623
00:37:09.480 --> 00:37:09.720
So

624
00:37:11.500 --> 00:37:15.440
our first meeting, we really wanted to get people talking, so we asked people,

625
00:37:15.510 --> 00:37:18.049
"What do you think is getting in the way?"

626
00:37:19.700 --> 00:37:23.460
And then based on that conversation, we analyzed all of the

627
00:37:23.500 --> 00:37:24.750
things that people came

628
00:37:25.860 --> 00:37:28.860
up with in the meeting and fed that back to them in the second meeting.

629
00:37:29.680 --> 00:37:32.770
And in that second meeting, we were able to rank the strategies in order of

630
00:37:32.840 --> 00:37:36.190
greatest importance and feasibility to identify the top three

631
00:37:36.900 --> 00:37:38.520
that they really wanted to dig into.

632
00:37:39.540 --> 00:37:43.400
And then we explored key issues surrounding the implementation to develop a

633
00:37:43.460 --> 00:37:46.200
plan and supports to make that plan

634
00:37:46.260 --> 00:37:47.580
implementable.

635
00:37:48.460 --> 00:37:52.340
We inventoried the proposed challenges from the multiple levels and the

636
00:37:52.380 --> 00:37:53.540
contextual factors

637
00:37:54.800 --> 00:37:58.550
and identified key resources to overcome barriers and

638
00:37:58.580 --> 00:37:59.080
supports.

639
00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:04.640
I'm going to show you some of the materials that we used, more of a

640
00:38:04.660 --> 00:38:08.520
how-to, but the brainstorming question was: What should we be

641
00:38:08.540 --> 00:38:12.300
considering when planning to implement colorectal cancer screening to improve

642
00:38:12.360 --> 00:38:14.160
rates for patients with diabetes?

643
00:38:14.580 --> 00:38:18.560
They came up with about 36 different things, so these are the top five.

644
00:38:18.880 --> 00:38:20.660
And there were two buckets. One was

645
00:38:21.840 --> 00:38:24.640
patient education and communication, and the other one was clinical flow.

646
00:38:25.320 --> 00:38:28.730
And so we fed these back to them in very much the language that they

647
00:38:28.980 --> 00:38:30.120
used when they said them.

648
00:38:32.380 --> 00:38:32.830
The second

649
00:38:35.200 --> 00:38:38.800
piece was looking at the clinical workflow process, so adding

650
00:38:38.860 --> 00:38:42.740
colorectal cancer screening as a part of routine diabetes care and informing

651
00:38:42.840 --> 00:38:46.480
patients, pop-up reminders in the EHR, diabetes

652
00:38:46.520 --> 00:38:50.330
educators. All of these map back to the ERIC Taxonomy of

653
00:38:50.400 --> 00:38:52.700
Implementation Strategies in different buckets.

654
00:38:54.400 --> 00:38:57.860
But we did not organize them in terms of those buckets just yet.

655
00:39:00.960 --> 00:39:04.660
We refined that list further in the second meeting and

656
00:39:04.740 --> 00:39:08.340
then used the ERIC Taxonomy of Implementation Strategies to

657
00:39:08.400 --> 00:39:11.270
adapt them to what that would look like for this

658
00:39:11.300 --> 00:39:15.100
particular change initiative. So instead of build a

659
00:39:15.160 --> 00:39:18.860
coalition, period, it was build a coalition, recruit, and cultivate

660
00:39:18.920 --> 00:39:21.120
relationships with partners and FQHCs to

661
00:39:22.140 --> 00:39:25.240
support the implementation effort to improve colorectal cancer screening.

662
00:39:25.280 --> 00:39:25.440
So,

663
00:39:26.340 --> 00:39:30.280
really explaining what that implementation strategy meant for the different

664
00:39:30.340 --> 00:39:31.280
members of the group.

665
00:39:35.280 --> 00:39:36.140
Then after we

666
00:39:37.520 --> 00:39:41.350
selected top strategies, we went through as a

667
00:39:41.420 --> 00:39:44.100
group, at what point of the implementation

668
00:39:44.120 --> 00:39:47.420
process would we need to be thinking about this strategy?

669
00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:50.920
Is this a pre-implementation or adoption consideration?

670
00:39:51.960 --> 00:39:55.520
Is this an implementation consideration or something for maintenance?

671
00:39:55.980 --> 00:39:58.960
So then we picked apart the strategy together as a group.

672
00:39:59.440 --> 00:40:02.940
Who is involved? What do we need them to do?

673
00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.500
What are the barriers and facilitators to them doing it?

674
00:40:07.860 --> 00:40:10.340
So the top four strategies that were

675
00:40:11.380 --> 00:40:15.300
selected by the group were identify and prepare champions, develop

676
00:40:15.340 --> 00:40:19.160
and distribute educational materials for colorectal cancer screening for

677
00:40:19.200 --> 00:40:22.760
patients with diabetes. There was a lot of

678
00:40:22.820 --> 00:40:25.780
caveats to these. So that second one was they needed to be

679
00:40:26.040 --> 00:40:29.860
low literacy. They needed to include

680
00:40:29.960 --> 00:40:33.830
how to do the different test type that they were prioritizing

681
00:40:33.900 --> 00:40:35.180
as their thing.

682
00:40:36.720 --> 00:40:39.220
And the other piece was that they needed to have control over

683
00:40:40.020 --> 00:40:41.340
how they were distributing them.

684
00:40:43.300 --> 00:40:46.320
Then develop and organize quality monitoring systems.

685
00:40:46.340 --> 00:40:49.880
In federally qualified health centers, UDS metrics, the Uniform Data System

686
00:40:49.940 --> 00:40:53.020
